(Returning refugees)

-	Pursuing durable solutions, and in particular, for 172,000 refugees in neighbouring countries who may wish to return (67,000 are budgeted within operating level);
-	NFI support to the most vulnerable refugees, including for winterization assistance for up to 30,000 families.
-	Operationlizing the Joint UNHCR/UNDP project to pursue reintegration activities, and in particular livelihood, for returning refugees and other community members;

The Operating Level will only allow the most basic elements of the UNHCR Afghanistan Operation to function.  Elements above operating level and are most crucial include:

-	Pursuing durable solutions, and in particular, for 105,000 refugees in neighbouring countries who may wish to return (67,000 are budgeted within operating level);
-	Support for the implementation of passed refugee legislation, and assistance to the Government of Afghanistan to put in place RSD mechanisms;
-	NFI support to the most vulnerable refugees, including for winterization assistance for up to 30,000 families.
-	Operationlizing the Joint UNHCR/UNDP project to pursue reintegration activities, and in particular livelihood, for returning refugees and other community members;
-	Assistance to facilitate IDP solutions, including return and local integration such as shelter, community-based activities, livelihood are budgeted above operating level for up to 50,000 families.

Returning refugees
UNHCR established a working group with the Ministry of Refugees and Reintegration to develop and begin implementing a revised approach to pursuing sustainable reintegration for returning refugees.  The Ministry established an inter-ministerial coordination committee, and through this mechanism, developed inputs and overall costings to undertake a three-year plan to address the disparity between returning refugees and other community members as well as address newly-arriving returnees.
Further to the 2010 London conference, National Priority Programmes were identified as a way to manage the civilian transition to full ownership by Afghan authorities of the development agenda.  There are a total of 23 National Priority Programmes, which as of March 2012, 15 are completed and the balance due to be finalized shortly, to be presented at a Conference in Tokyo in July 2012.  The 23 NPPs are managed within six clusters including:
- Security;
- Human Resource Development: (Skills Development and Labor, Education for All, Higher Education, Women Affairs, Capacity Building for Health);
- Infrastructure Development: (National Regional Resource Corridor, Extractive Industries, National Energy Program, Urban Development);
- Private Sector Development: (Trade Facilitation and SME, E-Afghanistan);
- Agriculture and Rural Development: (Water and Natural Resource Management, Comprehensive Agriculture, Rural Access, Strengthening Local Institutions);
- Governance: (Economic and Financial Reform, Transparency and Accountability, Efficient and Effective Government, Local Governance, Justice for ALL, Human Rights).
UNHCR participated in a number of targeted UN Country Team meetings to design and plan an inter-agency response to targeted high-return areas.  UNCT members who participated in these discussions included WFP, UNICEF, WHO, FAO, ILO, UNODC, Habitat, UN Macca, UNESCO, UNOCHA and IOM.

UNHCR signed an MOU with UNDP to establish a Joint Programme to pursue sustainable reintegration.  The development of this Joint Plan, if funded, would provide a platform for several UN agencies to work with various Government of Afghanistan ministries to undertake multi-sectorial community-based reintegration activities in 48 high-return communities.

IDPs
UNHCR as Protection Cluster lead has contributed substantially by negotiating for regular advice to the Humanitarian coordinator and to the Humanitarian Country Team on core protection issues in the country. This now helps drive the HCT agenda and enables comprehensive humanitarian approaches. Besides the dissemination of the previously produced documents and monitoring of their implementation, UNHCR as lead for the Protection cluster has further produced in 2011 comprehensive Protection Overviews for several regions of the country. The production of bi-annual Security Council Expert Group Notes on Protection of Civilians is another concrete task undertaken by UNHCR as Protection Cluster lead and brings along with it substantial advocacy, lobbying and briefings of stakeholders.   UNHCR also leads the Emergency Shelter/NFI cluster, which has helped to put in place standards related to minimal standards for NFI packages and coordinate emergency assistance to new displacement.  IOM is the deputy cluster lead, and is overall responsible for natural disaster internal displacement.

In addition, UNHCR led the IDP Task Force alongside the Ministry of Refugees and Repatriation, in Kabul as well as in six regional locations, including Kabul, Jalalabad, Gardez, Herat, Kandahar and Mazar.

UNHCR continued to engage partnerships at the national and in the field with NGOs, including through the ACBAR NGO coordination mechanism for advocacy and response.
